public class TestInterfaces {

	public static interface Test {
		public void test();
	}

	public static class MyTest implements Test {
		public void test() {
			System.out.println("test");
		}
	}

	public static void main(String... args) throws Exception {
		Test x = new MyTest() {
			@Override
			public void test() {
			}
		};

		System.out.println("interfaces implemented --- should be one (1): " +
x.getClass().getInterfaces().length);
	}
}

public static void main(String... args) throws Exception {
		Test x = new Test() {
			public void test() {
			}
		};

		System.out.println("interfaces implemented --- should be one (1): " +
x.getClass().getInterfaces().length);
	}

Bug.WithStack:
on running the following program, i observed zero (0) interfaces implemented at
runtime, when the answer should in fact be one (1):

package com.sac.mikea.util;

public class TestInterfaces {

	public static interface Test {
		public void test();
	}

	public static class MyTest implements Test {
		public void test() {
			System.out.println("test");
		}
	}

	public static void main(String... args) throws Exception {
		Test x = new MyTest() {
			@Override
			public void test() {
			}
		};

		System.out.println("interfaces implemented --- should be one (1): " +
x.getClass().getInterfaces().length);
	}
}
running on sun's jre1.5.0_05
Why do you expect 1?
MyTest.class.getInterfaces().length returns 1, but for the anonymous class of
MyTest the answer should be 0.
I tried with javac and I also get 0. What makes you believe that 1 is the right
answer?
thanks for your quick response. i didn't know that anonymous classes implement
no interfaces... do you have a reference to the java language specification for
that?

my impression was that since i could use "Test x" below,
x.getClass().getInterfaces() should also reflect that "x" can be cast to "Test".

best regards,
mike

If the anonymous class is an anonymous of an interface, I guess you can get 1.
For example:
	public static void main(String... args) throws Exception {
		Test x = new Test() {
			public void test() {
			}
		};

		System.out.println("interfaces implemented --- should be one (1): " +
x.getClass().getInterfaces().length);
	}

In your test case, you define an anonymous of a class. So why would it have a
interface?
The fact that x is defined as a Test doesn't change anything. This simply means
that the anonymous is in the hierarchy of the interface Test, but it doesn't
have a declared super interface. I think the javadoc is pretty clear:
http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/api/java/lang/Class.html#getInterfaces()
Best regards,
Closing as INVALID.

