source_code.code:
public class TestWorksheet
{
    public static void main (String [] args) {
        Display display = new Display ();
        Shell shell = new Shell (display);
        shell.setLayout (new FillLayout ());
        Table table = new Table (shell, SWT.NONE);
        table.setLinesVisible (true);
        table.setHeaderVisible (true);
        for (int i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
            TableColumn col = new TableColumn (table, SWT.NONE);
            col.setWidth (80);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
            TableItem item = new TableItem (table, SWT.NONE);
            for (int j = 0; j < 50; j++) {
                item.setText (j, "Cell " + i + " " + j);
            }
        }
        shell.open ();
        while (!shell.isDisposed ()) {
            if (!display.readAndDispatch ()) display.sleep ();
        }
    }
}

public class PR_116776 {
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		Display display = new Display();
		Shell shell = new Shell(display);
		shell.setLayout(new FillLayout());
		Table table = new Table(shell, SWT.NONE);
		table.setLinesVisible(true);
		table.setHeaderVisible(true);
		long t0 = System.currentTimeMillis();
		for (int i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
			TableColumn col = new TableColumn(table, SWT.NONE);
			col.setWidth(80);
		}
		for (int i = 0; i < 5000; i++) {
			TableItem item = new TableItem(table, SWT.NONE);
			for (int j = 0; j < 50; j++) {
				item.setText(j, "Cell " + i + " " + j);
			}
		}
		long t1 = System.currentTimeMillis();
		System.out.println("Time: " + (t1 - t0));
		shell.open();
		while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
			if (!display.readAndDispatch())
				display.sleep();
		}
	}
}

Bug.WithStack:
I was looking to see if SWT Table was suitable for basic Worksheet
functionality, just displaying a stream of data. I found the rendering when
scrolling on win32 to be unnacceptable compared to a similar application with
JTable. I'm currently investigating KTable.

import org.eclipse.swt.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.widgets.*;
import org.eclipse.swt.layout.*;

public class TestWorksheet
{
    public static void main (String [] args) {
        Display display = new Display ();
        Shell shell = new Shell (display);
        shell.setLayout (new FillLayout ());
        Table table = new Table (shell, SWT.NONE);
        table.setLinesVisible (true);
        table.setHeaderVisible (true);
        for (int i = 0; i < 50; i++) {
            TableColumn col = new TableColumn (table, SWT.NONE);
            col.setWidth (80);
        }
        for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++) {
            TableItem item = new TableItem (table, SWT.NONE);
            for (int j = 0; j < 50; j++) {
                item.setText (j, "Cell " + i + " " + j);
            }
        }
        shell.open ();
        while (!shell.isDisposed ()) {
            if (!display.readAndDispatch ()) display.sleep ();
        }
    }
}

On WindowsXP when I scroll horizontally sections of the screen visibly flash
white as they redraw - far too slowly. Vertically scrolling is better but if I
scroll fast enough it suffers from the same problem. KTable, in the provided
demos, seemed to fair much better.
1) If you run with the XP manifest, the flashing will go away.  See 
http://eclipse.org/swt/faq.php#xpthemes

2) The SWT table is the Windows ListView32 control that is used throughout 
Windows.  Can you confirm that the SWT table is flashing while other tables on 
the desktop (says the table of files in the Explorer) do not?  That would be 
great information.

3) There may be other reasons that the SWT table will not cut it as a 
Worksheet for you.  For example, it is not a spreadsheet control, so it 
doesn't have cell selection (although this can be achieved with the 
TableCursor class).  Regardless, I am still interested in fixing any flashing 
that SWT may have introduced in the native control.

Hope this helps.
I've added the manifest and the example no longer flashes but it is still slow.
Instead of flashing the scroll now lags while its redrawing. Not to worry, SWT
Table obviously isn't designed for this type of operation - I'll pour my efforts
into KTable. Out of interest how did this this fix the flashing?
We use LVS_EX_DOUBLEBUFFER that is only supported in version 6.0 and greater 
of the common controls.

> ... but it is still slow.

This concerns me as much as the flashing.  Can you confirm that the native 
tables on your desktop are fast while the SWT table is slow?  Like I said, the 
