>But anyway, as usual all the JNI calls are killing you.

Not so.  According to your previous post, 92% of the time is in Java (ie. "In the creating the table phase, the hotspot is Table.getColumnCount() (57% of cpu), and TableItem.<init>(Table, int) (35% of cpu)").  Table.getColumnCount() is a hotspot and any time spent in that method, JNI or not, will affect the results.
I meant those functions *and things they call* are hotspots, not the functions by themselves. You can see it better in the two html files in that zip I attached. Either the functions I listed are called too many times or cause too many JNI calls internally.
